body:
Prevent interacting with a blacklisted IPv4 if it is presented as IPv6, see #6521. To this end, `Blacklist` is modified to store `std::net::Ipv6Addr` (instead of `IpAddr`). When adding or querying an IPv4 address, it is [mapped to IPv6](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/net/struct.Ipv4Addr.html#method.to_ipv6_mapped).

The public interface of `Blacklist` remains unchanged, but `contains()` may return a different value.

```rust
use std::net::*;

let blacklist = Blacklist::from_iter(vec![
    "127.0.0.1".to_string(),
    "192.0.2.4:42".to_string(),
])

// Previously those would have returned false.
let ip_a = IpAddr::V6("::ffff:127.0.0.1".parse().unwrap());
let ip_b = IpAddr::V6("::ffff:192.0.2.4".parse().unwrap());
assert!(blacklist.contains(&SocketAddr::new(ip_a, 8080)));
assert!(blacklist.contains(&SocketAddr::new(ip_b, 42)));

// When querying an IPv4 the mapping happens implicitly.
let ip_v4 = IpAddr::V4(Ipv4Addr::new(127, 0, 0, 1));
assert!(blacklist.contains(&SocketAddr::new(ip_v4, 8080)));
```

Issue #6521

**Test plan:** Covered by existing tests.
